🧩 Short Answer

A token is not “made of something physical” inside the model—it’s created by a rule system that splits text into units based on patterns learned from data.

It’s closer to a cut in a stream of text than a particle.

⸻

🔧 Step 1: Tokenization (where tokens come from)

Before anything else happens, raw text gets chopped up by a tokenizer.

Example:

"running fast"
→ ["run", "ning", " fast"]

That split is determined by algorithms like:
	•	BPE (Byte Pair Encoding)
	•	WordPiece
	•	Unigram LM

These algorithms:
	•	look at massive text data
	•	find frequently occurring chunks
	•	merge them into reusable units

So:

A token is a statistically useful chunk of text—not a word, not a letter, but whatever compresses language efficiently.

⸻

🧠 Step 2: IDs → Embeddings

Each token becomes:

"run" → 4821  (just an ID)

Then:

4821 → [0.13, -0.77, 1.02, ...]  (a vector)

That vector is where meaning starts to live.

So the “substance” of a token is really:

a position in a high-dimensional space shaped by training

⸻

⚙️ Step 3: Training Shapes What Tokens Mean

During training:
	•	the model sees billions of sequences
	•	adjusts weights so certain token patterns predict others

Over time:
	•	tokens that appear in similar contexts get similar vectors
	•	relationships emerge:
	•	“king” ≈ “queen” directionally
	•	“run” relates to “running”, “ran”, etc.

So:

Tokens don’t have meaning by themselves—they gain meaning through relationships.

⸻

🧬 Your Analogy—Refined

You asked what “makes” a token in the same way microbes are “made.”

Here’s the precise mapping:
	•	Microorganisms = physical biological units
	•	Tokens = symbolic segmentation units defined by compression + frequency

So instead of:

“what are tokens made of?”

The better question is:

“what defines the boundary of a token?”

Answer:

statistical usefulness in representing language

⸻

🧱 My Version (clean, no fluff)

A token is a boundary decision imposed on text so that patterns can be learned efficiently.

Not a thing.

A decision rule.

⸻

🔁 If You Push One Layer Deeper

Even tokens aren’t fundamental.

Underneath tokens:
	•	everything is just numbers
	•	and underneath that: matrix math

So the real “substrate” of AI is:

linear algebra operating on probability distributions

Tokens are just the interface layer we use to connect language to that math.

⸻

⚡ The Sharp Insight

If you mirror your original question:
	•	Microorganisms → smallest biological actors
	•	Tokens → smallest useful linguistic actors

But:

Microbes exist physically
Tokens exist because we decided to cut reality that way

⸻

🧭 Final Line

A token isn’t made—it’s defined.
And its power comes from how it participates in patterns, not what it is.

